<html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
      xmlns:tal="http://xml.zope.org/namespaces/tal"
      xmlns:i18n="http://xml.zope.org/namespaces/i18n"
      xmlns:metal="http://xml.zope.org/namespaces/metal"
      metal:use-macro="context/@@partner/page"
      i18n:domain="cc_org">
<head>
  <title metal:fill-slot="title">Choose a License</title>
</head>
<body>
<div metal:fill-slot="body"
     tal:define="target_lang string:en;
                 stylesheet request/stylesheet | nothing;
                 exiturl    request/exit_url | string:'';
                 pd_exiturl python:exiturl.replace('&', '%26');
                 partner    request/partner | nothing;
                 partner_icon_url python: request.form.get('partner_icon_url','/images/remote_logo.gif');
                 show_jurisdiction request/jurisdiction_chooser | nothing;
                 def_juris request/jurisdiction | nothing;
                ">

<h1 i18n:translate="license.confirm_choice">Confirm Choice</h1>

<p i18n:translate="license.partner.pd_intro">Your choice suggests you
want to certify a work is in the public domain. The Public Domain
Certification is not a license. By using it you assert that a work is
already in the public domain.</p>

<style>.hidden{ display: none }</style>
  
<p i18n:translate="license.partner.pd.use_cc0">
If instead you want to waive copyright and neighboring rights on a work 
<span tal:omit-tag="" i18n:name="cc0_url" tal:content="string:/license/zero/partner?lang=${target_lang}&partner=${partner}&exit_url=${pd_exiturl}&license_code=publicdomain&stylesheet=${stylesheet}" />
  <em>in which you hold these rights</em>, choose <a href="${cc0_url}">CC0</a>.
</p>

<p i18n:translate="license.you_may_proceed">
<span tal:omit-tag="" i18n:name="processed_exit_url" 
      tal:content="view/exit_url">
You may now <a href="${processed_exit_url}">proceed</a>
</span>
</p>

</div>

</body>
</html>
